President Bill
Clinton?

19:09.148 --> 19:13.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMIE PARNES: I think that's a
really interesting
question, and a lot of us want
to know that.

19:14.020 --> 19:18.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She talked about making him
maybe an economic
adviser, and got a little bit of
pushback

19:18.691 --> 19:19.892 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for that.

19:19.925 --> 19:21.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think she is definitely
going to put
him to use.

19:21.127 --> 19:23.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is not going to have the
traditional spouse
role.

19:23.796 --> 19:27.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She will definitely, obviously,
send him to
Capitol Hill, I would think, to
work with

19:27.600 --> 19:29.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people that he knows.

19:29.402 --> 19:33.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she will probably host --
she and he maybe
will host meetings at the White
House for

19:33.539 --> 19:35.174 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
both Democrats and Republicans.

19:35.207 --> 19:38.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm sure that's something
that they want
to start right away.

19:38.677 --> 19:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Amie Parnes, Lisa
Desjardins, thank
you very much.

19:43.049 --> 19:50.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMIE PARNES: Thank you.

19:50.256 --> 19:58.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: This coming
Monday, in Cartagena,
Colombia, a peace deal will be
signed that

19:58.497 --> 20:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
aims to end more than 50 years
of war.

20:01.634 --> 20:07.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The accord also will mark the
end of the insurgency
by the revolutionary armed
forces of Colombia,

20:07.573 --> 20:09.041 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
known as the FARC.

20:09.075 --> 20:10.943 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has more.

20:10.976 --> 20:14.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All this week,
the guerrilla
group has been meeting at a
desolate location

20:14.613 --> 20:16.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Southern Colombia.

20:16.315 --> 20:21.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, unanimously, the FARC
voted to approve
the deal and form a new
political party.

20:21.921 --> 20:26.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After the signing this coming
Monday, the
accord must survive one more
hurdle, a nationwide

20:26.759 --> 20:29.628 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
popular referendum next weekend.

20:29.662 --> 20:33.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Nadja
Drost has been
at this meeting all week, and
joins me now.

20:33.566 --> 20:36.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nadja, we usually don't talk
about political
conventions in other countries.

20:36.202 --> 20:39.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the images that I have seen
from here
have sound stages, fog machines.

20:39.538 --> 20:41.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It seems almost like a musical
festival.

20:41.607 --> 20:43.709 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Give us a sense of what it was
like there.

20:43.742 --> 20:49.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: Well, to give you a
sense of
where we are, we are in the
middle of the

20:49.181 --> 20:53.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Colombian plains, essentially
the middle of
nowhere, and we're surrounded by
miles and

20:53.652 --> 20:55.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
miles of shrubland.

20:55.321 --> 21:01.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It might strike one as a strange
place to
hold an enormous conference, but
this is a

21:01.594 --> 21:09.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FARC stronghold and it has
significant historical
meaning for the rebel group.

21:09.735 --> 21:14.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The conference that the FARC has
been holding
here this week is historic.

21:14.440 --> 21:17.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is their final conference as
an armed group.

21:17.843 --> 21:23.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Here, they have made the
decision to terminate
their armed existence and they
have been plotting

21:23.282 --> 21:27.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their strategy to transform to a
political
party.

21:27.319 --> 21:31.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As you mentioned, there are
sound stages,
concerts.

21:31.724 --> 21:35.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are also guerrilla camps.

21:35.494 --> 21:37.496 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're really going all out.

21:37.530 --> 21:43.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It looks like the FARC are using
this as an
opportunity to introduce a new
face to the

21:43.969 --> 21:46.872 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Colombian and international
public.

21:46.906 --> 21:51.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With over 300 journalists here
camped out
in the middle of nowhere, it's a
chance for

21:51.710 --> 21:57.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the FARC to change the image of
them as a
narco-terrorist group to a group
of rebels

21:57.950 --> 22:02.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who very much want peace and
want to transform
themselves to become political
actors.

22:02.688 --> 22:05.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, so
what's the
next step here?

22:05.291 --> 22:07.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do they move forward to
disarm?

22:07.193 --> 22:13.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: If the peace
accords do receive
approval from the Colombian
public, then FARC

22:13.332 --> 22:19.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
troops, thousands of them, will
start mobilizing
themselves into large areas that
are being

22:19.205 --> 22:24.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
called zones of concentration,
where they
will stay put for six months as
they start

22:24.710 --> 22:27.012 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a gradual process of
disarmament.

22:27.046 --> 22:34.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But FARC leaders here this week
said that
they need assurance that an
amnesty law will

22:34.086 --> 22:37.790 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be passed before their troops
can move anywhere.

22:37.823 --> 22:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are demanding that they
have legal protections
to ensure their troops are not
going to get

22:43.862 --> 22:45.965 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
arrested as they move on that.

22:45.998 --> 22:50.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What are the
indications
in how that referendum vote will
go?

22:50.135 --> 22:54.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: It is leaning more
towards the
side of accepting the peace
deal.

22:54.773 --> 23:00.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, there is a very strong
campaign,
being led mostly by former
President Alvaro

23:00.779 --> 23:04.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Uribe, in rejection of the peace
deal.

23:04.250 --> 23:09.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, both sides of the
negotiation, both
the FARC and the government,
have made very

23:09.755 --> 23:15.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
clear that, if the no side wins,
if the public
rejects this peace deal, there
is no way that

23:15.928 --> 23:19.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they are going back to the
negotiating table.

23:19.565 --> 23:25.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
One of the FARC head
negotiators, Carlos Antonio
Lozada, told reporters that
there is not even

23:25.871 --> 23:27.640 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the remotest possibility.

23:27.673 --> 23:33.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And on the government side, it's
expected
that in the case that this
referendum fails

23:33.212 --> 23:39.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the peace process, then we will
likely not
see another negotiation for at
least 10 years.

23:39.518 --> 23:43.956 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So both the FARC and the
government are sending
a very strong message to the
public that this

23:43.989 --> 23:48.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is Colombia's best, if not
possibly last chance
for peace.

23:48.894 --> 23:51.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Nadja, you have
covered the FARC for a long
time.

23:51.597 --> 23:53.332 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How did we get to this point?

23:53.365 --> 23:57.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: There have been
many attempts
in the past decades to end this
conflict,

23:57.369 --> 24:01.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
both through negotiation or
through military
means.

24:01.373 --> 24:05.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Essentially, both sides have
become very tired
of war.

24:05.778 --> 24:09.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Colombia has lived now in 52
years of war.

24:09.148 --> 24:14.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The FARC has suffered year after
year of military
blows.

24:14.653 --> 24:16.355 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Their ranks have been shrinking.

24:16.388 --> 24:21.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And despite very strong military
campaigns,
the Colombian government has not
defeated

24:22.027 --> 24:23.829 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
them entirely.

24:23.862 --> 24:29.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think that it became clear
to both sides
that this war was going to be
intractable

24:29.668 --> 24:31.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
unless a negotiation took place.

24:31.737 --> 24:36.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
special correspondent
Nadja Drost joining us from
Colombia tonight,

24:36.041 --> 24:37.276 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
thanks so much.

24:37.309 --> 24:44.149 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NADJA DROST: Thank you so much.

24:44.183 --> 24:50.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the
analysis of Shields
and Brooks.

24:50.723 --> 24:54.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and
New York Times columnist David
Brooks.

24:54.927 --> 24:55.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome, gentlemen.

24:55.928 --> 24:57.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Judy.

24:57.763 --> 25:02.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, we turn to
the lead story
tonight and for the last few
nights, David,

25:02.568 --> 25:09.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
two more shootings in Tulsa and
Charlotte,
North Carolina, by police of
black men.

25:09.441 --> 25:10.743 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We're still getting the
information.

25:10.776 --> 25:15.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know the Tulsa policewoman
was charged
with manslaughter.

25:15.280 --> 25:17.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What are we to make of this, the
fact that
these keep happening?

25:17.883 --> 25:22.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, first of
all, the videos
are just harrowing and have an
effect on,

25:22.755 --> 25:25.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, all of us and an effect
on the national
mood.

25:25.257 --> 25:27.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's just this is a man losing
his life.

25:27.693 --> 25:30.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a wife losing her
husband.

25:30.396 --> 25:32.131 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
These are cops in the middle.

25:32.164 --> 25:34.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you can feel the pressure
building on
them as they don't know -- quite
know what

25:34.466 --> 25:35.434 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to do.

25:35.467 --> 25:37.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Beyond that, we don't really
know that much.

25:37.136 --> 25:41.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think these things -- these
particular
situations are always going to
happen.

25:41.874 --> 25:45.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it seems to me there are two
issues here,
one, getting justice in the
individual case

25:45.644 --> 25:50.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or these individual cases and
all the individual
cases, and then, second, which
is to me more

25:50.649 --> 25:57.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
serious and the more political
subject, is,
we do know there is tremendous
racial disparities

25:57.623 --> 26:03.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in searches, in arrests, in all
sorts of police
activities, maybe not in police
killings.

26:03.061 --> 26:06.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Harvard Research shows there is
not much racial
disparity there, but just about
in every other

26:06.799 --> 26:09.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
police activity, there are these
huge racial
disparities.

26:09.568 --> 26:13.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we see the protests, at
least the
legitimate parts of the
protests, that's the

26:13.605 --> 26:15.407 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
problem.

26:15.441 --> 26:17.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so some -- I think it's
useful to separate
these individual cases -- and we
don't know

26:18.010 --> 26:22.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what happened here yet -- from
the larger
problem, which is indisputable.

26:22.347 --> 26:25.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And finding a solution to that
larger problem
is really the political issue.

26:25.484 --> 26:27.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

26:27.319 --> 26:32.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And can we focus on the real
problem, Mark,
when we have these -- when
feelings run high,

26:32.291 --> 26:33.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
emotions run high,
understandably?

26:33.559 --> 26:35.427 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes, I'm not sure.

26:35.461 --> 26:38.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't think really we have so
far, certainly.

26:38.397 --> 26:40.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, there's -- I agree with
David.

26:40.165 --> 26:43.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is so incredible -- it's
wrenching and
it's sobering.

26:43.702 --> 26:51.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my own perspective on it has
changed since
Senator Tim Scott, the
African-American Republican

26:51.376 --> 26:56.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from South Carolina, took to the
Senate floor,
a card-carrying conservative, an
authentic

26:56.548 --> 27:03.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
conservative man, ran as such,
got elected
and reelected as such, and said
-- spoke about

27:03.255 --> 27:11.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his own experience of being
stopped seven
times by police officers for the
principal

27:11.296 --> 27:18.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
offense of, as he put it,
driving a new car
in the wrong neighborhood, or
even being stopped

27:18.403 --> 27:22.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by Capitol Police and demanded
to show his
I.D.

27:22.975 --> 27:29.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It does give you an idea that
this is a real
problem understanding fully the
pressures

27:30.015 --> 27:34.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that David talked about and the
risks that
police officers do take.

27:34.486 --> 27:36.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening. I'm
Judy Woodruff.

27:36.388 --> 27:37.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight:
Dramatic cell phone
video taken by the wife of the
victim in this

27:37.890 --> 27:39.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
week's deadly encounter with
Charlotte police
raises even more questions.

27:39.691 --> 27:41.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
